text.headline: Overview
text.text:
The instrument has a spruce top while the rest is made of maple wood. The length is approximately 44/47 centimeters. Gasparo da Salò made the bridge particularly high and constructed a relatively short vibrating string. Thanks to this, the distance between the notes is not excessive, which allows for easy playing even on such a large instrument.

text.headline: ƒ-hole
text.text:
The ƒƒ (effe) are a type of resonance holes present on the soundboard of various musical instruments, such as those in the violin family and archtop acoustic guitars. The name derives from their shape, which resembles the cursive letter ƒ. Resonance holes with this particular shape are typical of Gasparo da Salò.

text.headline: Scroll
text.text:
The scroll is the end part of the neck of instruments belonging to the string family, namely, violin, viola, cello, and double bass. The scroll of this viola is not original and is probably by the luthier Lorenzo Storioni (Cremona 1751-1799).

text.headline: Fingerboard
text.text:
The fingerboard is a wooden surface on which one or more strings can be pressed to determine the note played, altering the basic pitch given by the open string. Due to this characteristic, the fingerboard is subject to wear and is replaced over time. In fact, the fingerboard of this viola is not original. Given the period in which this instrument was built, the original fingerboard was likely decorated.
